{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01VM5i4DCN8dyukpwXZQwDEa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012A5Ut7BYK3dGDhn7HuGRxD","name":"mcp__loop__get_page","input":{"workspaceId":"T0RTUHxtaWNyb3NvZnQuc2hhcmVwb2ludC1kZi5jb218YiFsUlpRZmVUWlEwQzlJb1J3RzVwcUFpQXJTV3lSOE5wQmlvcVZ6TGozTUc5Ri0zUlFmMGNyUW9rSTdmMUlwaWhTfDAxS1hKV1Q1N0VLUUxYWFdEM1NaQzJENDIyV0pDN0NNVkQ=","pageId":"bWljcm9zb2Z0LnNoYXJlcG9pbnQtZGYuY29tLGIhbFJaUWZlVFpRMEM5SW9Sd0c1cHFBaUFyU1d5UjhOcEJpb3FWekxqM01HOUYtM1JRZjBjclFva0k3ZjFJcGloUywwMUtYSldUNVo1SzNBTjM2N1NTSkZLV1RZUU9KTTNBMzdJ"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":248,"cache_read_input_tokens":33865,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":248,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":12,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"391681e2-3487-4c99-b8bf-9a9bee63c948","uuid":"76c137d3-46ae-49fd-ae43-4313df79d4c5"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012A5Ut7BYK3dGDhn7HuGRxD","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"id\": \"bWljcm9zb2Z0LnNoYXJlcG9pbnQtZGYuY29tLGIhbFJaUWZlVFpRMEM5SW9Sd0c1cHFBaUFyU1d5UjhOcEJpb3FWekxqM01HOUYtM1JRZjBjclFva0k3ZjFJcGloUywwMUtYSldUNVo1SzNBTjM2N1NTSkZLV1RZUU9KTTNBMzdJ\",\n  \"title\": \"Korean Food Culture\",\n  \"content\": \"# Korean Food Culture\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nKorean cuisine (**hansik**, 한식) is one of the world's most vibrant and flavorful food traditions. Rooted in centuries of agricultural practice, Confucian philosophy, and seasonal eating, Korean food culture emphasizes balance, fermentation, and communal dining.\\n\\n## Core Principles\\n\\n### Bap and Banchan (밥과 반찬)\\n\\nA traditional Korean meal centers on **bap** (steamed rice) accompanied by an array of **banchan** (side dishes). A typical home meal includes 3-5 banchan, while formal occasions may feature 12 or more. This structure reflects the Korean value of variety and nutritional balance.\\n\\n### The Five Flavors and Five Colors\\n\\nKorean cooking follows the principle of **obangsaek** (오방색) — five colors (white, black, red, yellow, green) representing five elements and directions. Dishes also balance five tastes: sweet, sour, salty, bitter, and spicy.\\n\\n### Fermentation (발효)\\n\\nKorea has one of the world's richest fermentation traditions. Fermented foods are central to daily meals and include:\\n\\n- **Kimchi** (김치) — fermented vegetables, most commonly napa cabbage\\n- **Doenjang** (된장) — fermented soybean paste\\n- **Gochujang** (고추장) — fermented red chili paste\\n- **Jeotgal** (젓갈) — salted and fermented seafood\\n- **Makgeolli** (막걸리) — fermented rice wine\\n\\n## Iconic Dishes\\n\\n### Kimchi (김치)\\n\\nMore than just a side dish, kimchi is a cultural symbol. With over 200 varieties, it is made year-round but traditionally prepared in bulk during **kimjang** (김장), a communal late-autumn event recognized by UNESCO as an Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity.\\n\\n### Bibimbap (비빔밥)\\n\\nLiterally meaning \\\"mixed rice,\\\" bibimbap is a colorful bowl of rice topped with sauteed vegetables, gochujang, and often a fried egg or sliced meat. Each region has its own variation, with Jeonju bibimbap being the most famous.\\n\\n### Korean BBQ (고기구이)\\n\\nGrilling meat at the table is a beloved social dining experience. Popular cuts include **samgyeopsal** (pork belly), **galbi** (short ribs), and **bulgogi** (marinated beef). The meal is always accompanied by lettuce wraps, ssamjang dipping sauce, and banchan.\\n\\n### Jjigae and Tang (찌개와 탕)\\n\\nStews and soups are essential to Korean meals:\\n\\n- **Kimchi jjigae** — kimchi stew with pork or tuna\\n- **Doenjang jjigae** — soybean paste stew with vegetables\\n- **Sundubu jjigae** — soft tofu stew\\n- **Samgyetang** (삼계탕) — ginseng chicken soup, a summer stamina dish\\n\\n## Dining Etiquette\\n\\n- Elders eat first; younger diners wait before beginning\\n- Rice and soup bowls stay on the table (not lifted)\\n- Metal chopsticks and a long-handled spoon are used together\\n- Pouring drinks for others (especially elders) is a sign of respect\\n- Sharing dishes from common plates is the norm\\n\\n## Street Food Culture (길거리 음식)\\n\\nKorean street food is a world unto itself. Markets like **Gwangjang Market** and **Myeongdong** in Seoul offer:\\n\\n- **Tteokbokki** (떡볶이) — spicy rice cakes\\n- **Hotteok** (호떡) — sweet filled pancakes\\n- **Gimbap** (김밥) — seaweed rice rolls\\n- **Sundae** (순대) — blood sausage\\n- **Bungeoppang** (붕어빵) — fish-shaped pastry with sweet red bean filling\\n\\n## Modern Trends\\n\\nKorean food culture continues to evolve with the global **hallyu** (Korean Wave). K-food has gained worldwide popularity, with Korean fried chicken, instant ramyeon, and convenience store culture becoming global phenomena. The rise of **mukbang** (먹방) — eating broadcast videos — has further amplified Korean food's international reach.\\n\\n## Seasonal and Festive Foods\\n\\n- **Tteokguk** (떡국) — rice cake soup eaten on Lunar New Year\\n- **Songpyeon** (송편) — half-moon rice cakes for Chuseok (harvest festival)\\n- **Patbingsu** (팥빙수) — shaved ice dessert enjoyed in summer\\n- **Naengmyeon** (냉면) — cold buckwheat noodles, a summer favorite\\n\\n\"\n}"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"391681e2-3487-4c99-b8bf-9a9bee63c948","uuid":"9575618c-18b4-4ff9-bd33-4fa9d6ec87fc","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"id\": \"bWljcm9zb2Z0LnNoYXJlcG9pbnQtZGYuY29tLGIhbFJaUWZlVFpRMEM5SW9Sd0c1cHFBaUFyU1d5UjhOcEJpb3FWekxqM01HOUYtM1JRZjBjclFva0k3ZjFJcGloUywwMUtYSldUNVo1SzNBTjM2N1NTSkZLV1RZUU9KTTNBMzdJ\",\n  \"title\": \"Korean Food Culture\",\n  \"content\": \"# Korean Food Culture\\n\\n## Overview\\n\\nKorean cuisine (**hansik**, 한식) is one of the world's most vibrant and flavorful food traditions. Rooted in centuries of agricultural practice, Confucian philosophy, and seasonal eating, Korean food culture emphasizes balance, fermentation, and communal dining.\\n\\n## Core Principles\\n\\n### Bap and Banchan (밥과 반찬)\\n\\nA traditional Korean meal centers on **bap** (steamed rice) accompanied by an array of **banchan** (side dishes). A typical home meal includes 3-5 banchan, while formal occasions may feature 12 or more. This structure reflects the Korean value of variety and nutritional balance.\\n\\n### The Five Flavors and Five Colors\\n\\nKorean cooking follows the principle of **obangsaek** (오방색) — five colors (white, black, red, yellow, green) representing five elements and directions. Dishes also balance five tastes: sweet, sour, salty, bitter, and spicy.\\n\\n### Fermentation (발효)\\n\\nKorea has one of the world's richest fermentation traditions. Fermented foods are central to daily meals and include:\\n\\n- **Kimchi** (김치) — fermented vegetables, most commonly napa cabbage\\n- **Doenjang** (된장) — fermented soybean paste\\n- **Gochujang** (고추장) — fermented red chili paste\\n- **Jeotgal** (젓갈) — salted and fermented seafood\\n- **Makgeolli** (막걸리) — fermented rice wine\\n\\n## Iconic Dishes\\n\\n### Kimchi (김치)\\n\\nMore than just a side dish, kimchi is a cultural symbol. With over 200 varieties, it is made year-round but traditionally prepared in bulk during **kimjang** (김장), a communal late-autumn event recognized by UNESCO as an Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity.\\n\\n### Bibimbap (비빔밥)\\n\\nLiterally meaning \\\"mixed rice,\\\" bibimbap is a colorful bowl of rice topped with sauteed vegetables, gochujang, and often a fried egg or sliced meat. Each region has its own variation, with Jeonju bibimbap being the most famous.\\n\\n### Korean BBQ (고기구이)\\n\\nGrilling meat at the table is a beloved social dining experience. Popular cuts include **samgyeopsal** (pork belly), **galbi** (short ribs), and **bulgogi** (marinated beef). The meal is always accompanied by lettuce wraps, ssamjang dipping sauce, and banchan.\\n\\n### Jjigae and Tang (찌개와 탕)\\n\\nStews and soups are essential to Korean meals:\\n\\n- **Kimchi jjigae** — kimchi stew with pork or tuna\\n- **Doenjang jjigae** — soybean paste stew with vegetables\\n- **Sundubu jjigae** — soft tofu stew\\n- **Samgyetang** (삼계탕) — ginseng chicken soup, a summer stamina dish\\n\\n## Dining Etiquette\\n\\n- Elders eat first; younger diners wait before beginning\\n- Rice and soup bowls stay on the table (not lifted)\\n- Metal chopsticks and a long-handled spoon are used together\\n- Pouring drinks for others (especially elders) is a sign of respect\\n- Sharing dishes from common plates is the norm\\n\\n## Street Food Culture (길거리 음식)\\n\\nKorean street food is a world unto itself. Markets like **Gwangjang Market** and **Myeongdong** in Seoul offer:\\n\\n- **Tteokbokki** (떡볶이) — spicy rice cakes\\n- **Hotteok** (호떡) — sweet filled pancakes\\n- **Gimbap** (김밥) — seaweed rice rolls\\n- **Sundae** (순대) — blood sausage\\n- **Bungeoppang** (붕어빵) — fish-shaped pastry with sweet red bean filling\\n\\n## Modern Trends\\n\\nKorean food culture continues to evolve with the global **hallyu** (Korean Wave). K-food has gained worldwide popularity, with Korean fried chicken, instant ramyeon, and convenience store culture becoming global phenomena. The rise of **mukbang** (먹방) — eating broadcast videos — has further amplified Korean food's international reach.\\n\\n## Seasonal and Festive Foods\\n\\n- **Tteokguk** (떡국) — rice cake soup eaten on Lunar New Year\\n- **Songpyeon** (송편) — half-moon rice cakes for Chuseok (harvest festival)\\n- **Patbingsu** (팥빙수) — shaved ice dessert enjoyed in summer\\n- **Naengmyeon** (냉면) — cold buckwheat noodles, a summer favorite\\n\\n\"\n}"}]}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01PxkGc3P97pCR5C8pQ8fhDf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Got it! The page is accessible and contains content about **Korean Food Culture**. Here's a summary:\n\n---\n\n## Summary: Korean Food Culture (Loop Page)\n\nThis Loop page is an overview of **Korean cuisine (hansik, 한식)**, covering its traditions, key principles, iconic dishes, and modern trends.\n\n### Key Sections:\n\n1. **Core Principles** — Korean meals center on rice (bap) with side dishes (banchan), follow the five-color/five-flavor philosophy (obangsaek), and heavily feature **fermentation** (kimchi, doenjang, gochujang, jeotgal, makgeolli).\n\n2. **Iconic Dishes** — Highlights kimchi (200+ varieties, UNESCO-recognized kimjang tradition), bibimbap, Korean BBQ (samgyeopsal, galbi, bulgogi), and stews/soups (jjigae, samgyetang).\n\n3. **Dining Etiquette** — Elders eat first, bowls stay on the table, metal chopsticks + long spoon, pouring drinks for elders, communal sharing.\n\n4. **Street Food** — Covers popular items like tteokbokki, hotteok, gimbap, sundae, and bungeoppang from markets like Gwangjang and Myeongdong.\n\n5. **Modern Trends** — Korean food's global rise via hallyu (Korean Wave), K-fried chicken, instant ramyeon, convenience store culture, and mukbang.\n\n6. **Seasonal/Festive Foods** — Tteokguk (Lunar New Year), songpyeon (Chuseok), patbingsu and naengmyeon (summer).\n\n---\n\nThis appears to be a general reference/educational document about Korean food culture — not a technical design doc or work item. No implementation action needed. Let me write up my learnings."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1994,"cache_read_input_tokens":34113,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1994,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"context_management":null},"parent_to